const summary = "'`Dataset ds001_aml contained ${n} patients and an overall objective_response rate of ${pct(rate(() => true).rate)}. I tested 48 self-contained hypotheses over 25 iterations using response-rate contrasts, subgroup difference-in-differences, and a robust linear probability model with demographics, AML biology, disease burden, inflammatory/nutritional markers, and treatment indicators. Effect estimates in transcript.json are signed absolute response-probability differences unless noted as adjusted linear probability coefficients.'"\\n\\nThe dominant treatment pattern was not a broad treatment main effect but a strong treatment-by-fitness interaction. treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine had a positive unadjusted main association (+"'${num(ven.effect)}), but this came entirely from unfit_for_intensive patients: among unfit patients the treated response rate was ${pct(venUnfit.a.rate)} vs ${pct(venUnfit.b.rate)} untreated (+${num(venUnfit.effect)}, p=${num(venUnfit.p)}), whereas among fit patients the treated rate was slightly lower (${pct(venFit.a.rate)} vs ${pct(venFit.b.rate)}, ${num(venFit.effect)}, p=${num(venFit.p)}). The venetoclax/azacitidine-by-unfit difference-in-differences was +${num(venUnfitDid.effect)}, and the adjusted model retained the interaction (+${num(fullModel.ven_aza_x_unfit.effect)}, p=${num(fullModel.ven_aza_x_unfit.p)}). treatment_7plus3 showed no meaningful overall or unfit-specific advantage.'"\\n\\nThe strongest biomarker signal was npm1_mutation. Overall response was "'${pct(npm1.a.rate)} in NPM1-mutated patients vs ${pct(npm1.b.rate)} in wildtype patients (+${num(npm1.effect)}, p=${num(npm1.p)}). This signal was highly context-dependent: in venetoclax/azacitidine-treated patients the NPM1 difference was +${num(npm1Ven.effect)}, while in untreated/non-venetoclax patients it was ${num(npm1NoVen.effect)}. The unfit + venetoclax/azacitidine + NPM1 subgroup was particularly enriched for response (${pct(npm1UnfitVen.a.rate)} vs ${pct(npm1UnfitVen.b.rate)}, +${num(npm1UnfitVen.effect)}, p=${num(npm1UnfitVen.p)}), whereas unfit patients not receiving venetoclax/azacitidine had no NPM1 advantage (${num(npm1UnfitNoVen.effect)}, p=${num(npm1UnfitNoVen.p)}).'"\\n\\nAdverse-risk biology blunted favorable NPM1 and venetoclax/azacitidine patterns. tp53_mutation lowered response overall ("'${num(tp53.effect)}, p=${num(tp53.p)}) and eliminated the NPM1 advantage: NPM1 was favorable in TP53-wildtype disease (+${num(npm1Tp53Neg.effect)}) but not in TP53-mutated disease (${num(npm1Tp53Pos.effect)}), yielding a negative interaction of ${num(npm1Tp53Did.effect)}. TP53 mutation also removed the venetoclax/azacitidine advantage (${num(venTp53Did.effect)} difference-in-differences). complex_karyotype was independently adverse (${num(complex.effect)}, adjusted ${num(fullModel.complex_karyotype.effect)}) and similarly attenuated NPM1 benefit: NPM1 was favorable in non-complex karyotype (+${num(npm1ComplexNeg.effect)}) but not in complex karyotype (${num(npm1ComplexPos.effect)}).'"\\n\\nDisease burden, performance status, nutritional status, and inflammation were clinically coherent. ecog_ps >=1, ecog_ps=2, weight_loss_pct_6mo >=5, albumin_g_dl <3.5, blast_pct_marrow >=70, wbc_k_per_ul >=50, and crp_mg_l >=10 were all associated with lower response. In the adjusted model, ecog_ps ("'${num(fullModel.ecog_ps.effect)} per ECOG step), weight_loss_pct_6mo (${num(fullModel.weight_loss_pct_6mo_z.effect)} per SD), albumin_g_dl (+${num(fullModel.albumin_g_dl_z.effect)} per SD), blast_pct_marrow (${num(fullModel.blast_pct_marrow_z.effect)} per SD), and crp_mg_l (${num(fullModel.crp_mg_l_z.effect)} per SD) remained significant. NLR >=5 had a small negative estimate but was not significant.'"\\n\\nSeveral clinically plausible but unsupported hypotheses were refuted. FLT3-ITD, FLT3-TKD, IDH1, and IDH2 mutation status had no significant univariate response association. Within marker-positive subgroups, midostaurin for FLT3-ITD, gilteritinib for FLT3-ITD, ivosidenib for IDH1, and enasidenib for IDH2 did not show statistically significant response improvements in this cohort. secondary_aml and sex_female also were not significant. Solid-tumor-oriented markers in this AML file (her2_amplification, met_exon14_skipping, ret_fusion, ros1_fusion) had near-zero, non-significant response differences and behaved as negative controls.\\n\\nOverall, the cohort's response structure is dominated by an NPM1-enriched venetoclax/azacitidine-sensitive subgroup among patients unfit for intensive therapy, counterbalanced by adverse TP53 and complex-karyotype biology and by general clinical frailty/disease-burden markers. Mutation-treatment relationships expected for FLT3 and IDH targeted agents were not supported by these observational response contrasts."'`;

